    <fr:title text="Kronecker delta">Kronecker delta</fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
    <fr:date>
      <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
      <fr:month>5</fr:month>
      <fr:day>26</fr:day>
    </fr:date>
    <fr:authors>
      <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
    </fr:authors>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>The Kronecker delta, denoted <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\delta _{ij}]]></fr:tex>, is a function of two variables, usually integers, that is 1 if the variables are equal and 0 otherwise. Formally:</fr:p>
    <fr:p>
      <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\delta _{ij} =  \begin {cases}  1 & \text {if } i = j \\ 0 & \text {if } i \neq  j \end {cases}]]></fr:tex>
    </fr:p>
    <fr:p>The Kronecker delta is widely used in many areas of mathematics, including linear algebra, tensor calculus, and functional analysis. In the context of <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001H.xml" addr="FA-001H" title="Orthonormal set">orthonormal sets</fr:link> or bases in a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000U.xml" addr="FA-000U" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert space</fr:link>, the inner product of basis elements is given by the Kronecker delta:</fr:p>
    <fr:p>
      <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  e_i, e_j \rangle  = \delta _{ij}]]></fr:tex>
    </fr:p>
    <fr:p>This expresses the fact that the basis elements are orthogonal to each other (<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  e_i, e_j \rangle  = 0]]></fr:tex> for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i \neq  j]]></fr:tex>) and have unit norm (<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  e_i, e_i \rangle  = 1]]></fr:tex>).</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter>
